description.plain:
Bryson Tiller is an American singer-songwriter from Louisville, Kentucky.

Bryson’s success didn’t happen overnight. Bryson released Killer Instinct back in 2011. At the same time, he worked two jobs whilst also dealing with relationship issues. At one point, Bryson even considered applying for a third job to provide for his newborn daughter, Harley, who is featured in the True To Self cover art.

Bryson’s life changed forever with the release of his breakout single “Don’t,” which he dropped on SoundCloud in 2014 and has since been streamed over 35 million times. With the release of this track, Tiller began receiving attention from music industry insiders, receiving early co-signs from super-producer Timbaland and rapper Drake. This led to multiple major label deals for Bryson, one of those being an OVO contract from Drizzy, but Bryson surprisingly declined the offer. Later, Bryson chose to sign a creative partnership with RCA Records on August 25, 2015.

Since the release of “Don’t,” Bryson has dropped three albums: his debut studio album, T R A P S O U L, in 2015, True To Self in 2017, and A N N I V E R S A R Y in 2020, precisely five years after the release of his debut album.

songs.title: Exchange

description.plain:
The second single off Bryson Tiller’s 2015 debut album, “Exchange” is an ode to an ex. Bryson gets personal about a past break-up and fantasizes about igniting an old flame. The play on word’s in the song’s title (“ex’s change”) is reflected in the second verse.

The song’s instrumental samples K.P. & Envyi’s “Shorty Swing My Way” and is considered a T R A P S O U L highlight. “Exchange” charted for weeks on the Billboard Hot 100.

The official music video was directed by the award-winning Rohan Blair-Mangat.

songs.title: Sorry Not Sorry

description.plain:
This song sees Bryson addressing a girl he dated pre-fame. Since blowing up, she wants to rekindle their romance. Bryson isn’t having any of it. This may be same girl he raps about on “Overtime.”

During an interview with Billboard, Tiller revealed this song was given to him by Timbaland and he recorded it in his hotel room:

One was “Sorry Not Sorry” and the other one was “Been That Way” and I recorded both of them in my hotel. I was going to record it at the Hit Factory, but I told Tim I don’t really like recording in big studios, so he bought me a whole bunch of equipment to record in my hotel.
